lter’, while the origin of the Lincolnshire placename is uncertain. Compare   Holtham  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Holtham","meanings":["English:","habitational name from a place so named or a topographic name for someone who lived ‘(at the) enclosure in the wood’, from Middle English <i>holt</i> ‘wood, grove’ + <i>ham</i> ‘enclosure’ (Old English <i>holt</i> + <i>hamm</i>). Compare   Haltom   and   Holtom  .","variant of   Hotham  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Hotham was born in 1158, in Hotham, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Durand Hotham, was 26 and his mother, Mrs. Durand Hotham, was 22. He had at least 2 sons with Agnes Arundell. He died in 1210, in his hometown, at the age of 52."},"et":{"1158–1210":"1158–1210","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","1183–1222":"1183–1222","1200–1249":"1200–1249","1133–1175":"1133–1175","1137–Female":"1137–Surnud","about 1183":"umbes 1183","1249":"1249","1137":"1137","1158":"1158","1200":"1200","1222":"1222","1210":"1210","1133":"1133"